ility of error does a disservice to poets and their poems.Tracing the temptation to justify poets' errors from Aristotle through Freud, McAlpine demonstrates that the study of poetry's mistakes is also a study of critical attitudes toward mistakes, which are usually too generous-and often at the expense of the poet's intentions. Through remarkable close readings of Wordsworth, Keats, Browning, Clare, Dickinson, Crane, Bishop, Heaney, Ashbery, and others, The Poet's Mistake shows that errors are an inevitable part of poetry's making and that our responses to them reveal a great deal about our faith in poetry-and about how we read.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAmerican poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and cricitism. 0aErrors and blunders, LiteraryxHistory. 0aErrors and blunders, Literary. 0aPoetryxAuthorship. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh  aAnxiety of Influence.  aChristopher Ricks.  aElizabeth Bishop.  aEmily Dickinson.  aForce of Poetry.  aFrank Kermode.  aGeoffrey Hill.  aHarold Bloom.  aHart Crane.  aJohn Ashbery.  aJohn Clare.  aJohn Fuller.  aJohn Keats.  aJohn Sutherland.  aLiterature and Matters of Fact.  aMichael Anesko.  aNerys Williams.  aPaul Muldoon.  aRobert Browning.  aRomantic poetry.  aSeamus Heaney.  aSeth Lerer.  aUses of Error.  aWho Framed Elizabeth Bennet.  aWho is Ozymandias.  aWilliam Wordsworth.  acontemporary poetry.  aerrors.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary history.  amisprision.  amodernist poetry.  apoetry criticism.  atypos.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBO